The fix should be to skip unreachable blocks when determining the insertion point. If all blocks are unreachable, we should place the insertion point at the function entry or skip vectorization.

Let me look at the `FindLastInst` lambda again. When comparing two instructions:
- If `LastInst` is in an unreachable block, it updates `LastInst = I`
- If `I` is in an unreachable block, it continues (keeps current `LastInst`)

So if we have multiple instructions in unreachable blocks, it will pick the first one it encounters (or one of them). This is wrong because unreachable blocks don't dominate each other.

The fix should be: when comparing instructions from different blocks, if one is unreachable and the other is reachable, pick the reachable one. If both are unreachable, we should not pick either - we should find a reachable insertion point or skip vectorization.

Actually, looking at the code again: if `LastInst` is unreachable and `I` is also unreachable, it updates `LastInst = I` (line 15976). This means it will pick some unreachable instruction as the insertion point.

